description.text: Four months ago, my daughter had given us a pretty good sized picture frame. The frame weighs a good 15 pounds or so because of panes of glass on both the front & rear. When I tried to hang it on the wall I found that the hanger brackets that came with it were designed for a fastener or hook with a very small & low profile head, like a 18 gauge wire nail, which would not hold this thing very well. In order for me to use drywall anchors and either something more like a #6 pan head screw, I needed either a different hanger or change the existing hanger to accept the larger fastener. So as my first project after assembling the printer and printing the Geeetech "test disk and a calibration cube (four months ago) I did a quick learn on how to use Autodesk 123D and came up with this simply designed spacer for the existing hanger. It allowed me to use the larger headed screw with a drywall anchor and I was very happy that the dimensions were perfect on my first try. Using the 3D printer to help us hang the picture was a huge confidence builder and my wife was impressed enough to give he endorsement on my 3D printer related purchases since then. Win-win! :-)

description.text:
This is a printable bracket for the Iowa Scaled Engineering MRServo-1 model railroad servo switch machines. It's designed to hold both the control electronics and the 9g servo, and provide the ability to adjust back and forth to get the throw distance just right.

The part was designed in Fusion 360, but I've included the original f3d as well as more open IGS and STP files.

I recommend a #8 1/2" lath screw for actually mounting the bracket to the layout benchwork. My preferred mounting method is to hold the assembled bracket up where it goes, mark the screw points, and then pre-drill them. I find it much easier to get the bracket screws accurately positioned this way.

Notes:

The dimensions on the part are exact, so you'll need to scale it up by the proper amount to adjust for thermal expansion in your print material. I recommend scaling up 2-2.5% for ABS.

  • bolt1 goes through the small hole in body_1 and attaches to dial. This allows dial to turn freely.
  • body_1 snaps onto body_2
  • joint_1 attaches body_2 and body_3
  • joint_2 attaches body_3, body_4 and body_5
  • barrel_connector attaches joint_2 and barrel_1
    • Tolerances are snug, so some sanding may be required. There is enough room in the grip to embed a small button switch behind the trigger and run wires into the body. An LED behind a natural (translucent) PLA barrel makes a cool glow effect.

title: Dual Head XY Offset Calibration Tool

description.text:
This tool is designed to assist with dual head nozzle offset calibration. You can customize this for your desired layer height, and also create a smaller or larger tool as per your requirements.

Within the customizer, selecting "extruder1" will always print the same thing regardless of the selected offset. By printing 0.2, 0.1, and 0.5 offset things for "extruder2" composited with the base from "extruder1", you can home in your offset calibration to 200, 100, and 50 micron accuracy in 3 steps, providing that you have a reasonably accurate starting point.

The tool is designed to home in with the minimum of filament used, opting to print only two layers at the configured layer height, thus completing quickly also.

I hope it helps someone out there.

title: Bicycle and Car iPhone 6 Plus Mount family

description.text:
I wanted a case + mount for my iPhone 6 Plus on my bicycle. A lot of the models on Thingiverse are for different cases or caseless iPhone dimensions. I made this model to work with the case I use: "Incipio NGP Case for iPhone 6+".

Source files on GitHub: Bicycle and Car iPhone 6 Plus Mount family

UPDATE 01-Apr-2016: Added a cupholder-based mount system that is designed and tested to work in a 1996 Dodge RAM 1500.

UPDATE 08-Apr-2016: Added a cupholder-based mount system, cupholder2_* that is designed and tested to work in a 2005 Mustang. Has a different orientation and configuration of the arm.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2X

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.20

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I printed the smaller Components in ABS at the listed settings, but PLA should be fine too..

The sleeve .STL has a truncated top so that it fits inside the print volume of a LulzBot Mini, or a Makerbot Replicator 2X. It prints at 30% infill at 0.20mm layer height (5.5 hours) in its vertical orientation in PLA.

Supports

Supports are needed on the Sleeve (for the cutouts for volume, power buttons, etc.)

cupholder_lid_bracket.stl prints well in that orientation and needs supports.

Parts for bike mount

Print the case sleeve, sleeve cap, bicycle mount, and (optionally) mount catch.

The bicycle mount needs a metal hose clamp or similar to attach to bicycle steering handlebar column.

An M2.5 screw (10mm) can be used to attach the mount catch to the mount. I just self-tapped a machine screw through them both.

Cupholder

Print the same case sleeve if you want another one to have.

There are four cupholder parts to print: cup, lid, lid_bracket, and coupler.

  1. Glue the lid to the cup. Plastic model cement and superglue work. Wait until it sets.
  2. Screw the lid bracket into the lid
  3. Insert the coupler into the lid bracket, and set orientation appropriately
  4. Fill the cup with coins, enough to weigh it down into the cupholder.

Modeled case dimensions in OpenSCAD

As part of solving this problem, I first used OpenSCAD to model the dimensions on the case.

Iterated in OpenSCAD and print experiments

Then I iterated using experimental prints until I got to sizing and access holes I was satisifed with.

Other pieces

Bike mount

  • 2.5M x 10 machine screw for OPTIONAL catch
  • metal hose clamp to attach bike mount to handlebar column

Cupholder mount

  • superglue, model cement glue, or other adhesive to glue lid to cup
  • 4(x) 3 0.5M x 8 machine screws to attach the lid bracket to the lid.
  • enough coins to fill the cup. Used to add weight to the the cupholder cup so that it stays setting.

This is my take on the various Klein Bottles, inspired in large part by Dizingof's perforated bottle. Mine, however, uses the Voronoi tesselation to perforate the bottle.  
Does not need support, but I suggest you print with brim to improve adhesion to the platform.

Made by using ViaCad and MeshLab, as follows (all the files are included):
  • In Viacad, I created 3 surfaces: the bottle body, the neck, and a patch that covers the intersection of the bottle and the neck. The bottle and neck were exported as very fine meshes, the patch as a regular resolution mesh.
  • In MeshLab, I imported the bottle and the patch.
  • Filters > Color... > Disk Vertex Coloring to color the Bottle using the points in the patch, adjusting the parameter until the patch was fully colored.
  • Render > Color > None and then Filters > Selection > Select Faces by Color. Select RGB mode, set the sliders all to 1, turn on Preview, and then tune down the R value until you get everything selected but the patch area.
  • Filters > Selection > Invert Selection, then Filters > Selection > Delete Selected Faces and Vertices to make the hole. It will be a bit bigger than the patch, but this is what you want, it makes for a nice effect.
  • This is a good point to save your work. MeshLab gets crashy if you do too much, so make a lot of checkpoints. As a general rule, if something is crashing MeshLab -- or not giving proper results -- get things to the point just before the crash, save, then restart MeshLab and import the saved mesh.
  • Turn off display of the patch, then Import the Neck. If the neck has a different shade from the bottle, then Filters > Normals > Invert Faces... to change the normals.
  • Filters > Mesh > Flatten... to combine the two meshes.
  • One problem you may run into is that the Voronoi Tesselation seems to mess up at the join between the neck and the bottle. To avoid this, use Filters > Cleaning > Merge Close... and set a pct of 8-10 (Try 8, if it doesn't work, backtrack and try bigger numbers.
  • Save the results and then do the Voronoi tesselation. See my Voronoi Tetrahedron for the details on how to do that. I suggest using about 250 points to do the tesselation.

description.text:
Adjustable Reel Bearing

Sized for 3/4" PVC pipe arbor. Can use 1/2" steel round stock with bushing. Will cover a 57-75 mm reel opening. 57, 60, 63, 66, 69, 72, 75 mm.

Printer:
Check bed/nozzle clearance. The 1st filament layer should be same as rest to try and get square edges. Best to print the rollers separate so the speed can be dialed down to 30-40% when the pins are printed. I would use a timer. Pins print in about the last 10 min or around the 6.3 mm height.

Cleanup:
Remove ridges on vertical edges, chamfer holes and flat sand components. A
finger/finger nail will help. Use a knife to slice down between the rows you plan to keep and the ones that can be cut away with a diagonal cutter.

Bearing Rollers:
I would start with the 15.5 mm roller. String them on a 7/32 drill bit by hand (pliers/rag). Spin the bit while holding file/sand paper to the rollers. Round is good. Next, Spin the bit while holding the outer most roller to clean the inside hole and remove one at a time. I also chamfered the holes. Running drill motor in reverse might help break them loose.

Can drill rollers with a #1 index bit for a 0.21 mm looser fit. Rollers should spin freely. Lube if desired.

Apply glue to hold bearing together. Same treatment with reel. Three drops of glue will do and make it easy to remove bearing when reel is empty for reuse. Can add tape to make a snug fit.

A race bushing is included. Two of these with a section of 3/4" PVC will allow the use of 1/2" round stock for an arbor.

This is a set of three Makerbot-printable objects that can be used for making models of Spanish Revival-style buildings.  I'm using these to build an HO (1/87) scale model of a 1920's era Drive-in Public Market (or what we'd call a strip mall.)  The main piece is an arched wall section that's 25.5 scale feet high and 20 feet wide (about 90 mm x 70 mm).  There's also a smaller piece with the same roofline intended for a tower, and a third piece for a storefront.

Check out my blog (http://vasonabranch.blogspot.com/2010/01/printing-1920s-drive-in-market.html, http://makerbot216.blogspot.com/2010/01/theres-skeinforge-setting-for-that.html) for more photos and details about building your own model.
I built my model by printing four of each part, then used 1/16" sheet styrene and strip styrene for the rest of the model. To make the line of arches, I cut the side pillar off of two of the pieces, and edge glued all together. You might also design a separate model with the part missing to avoid some tedious cutting. I used plastic cement or ABS for many of the plastic joints, but had problems with some glue joints and fell back to super glue. Solvent-based plastic cements seemed to work better if I filed the surfaces beforehand.
To finish the models, I used vinyl spackle to fill rough surfaces and hide diagonal fill paths. I then used gesso and acrylic gel with pumice (from an art supply store) to get the final stucco-like finish. I painted the parts by spraying them with a warm gray enamel paint from a spray can, then used white gesso mixed with a bit of raw umber to get the warm white finish on the walls. Interesting details about the parts Inspired by the Brio track's base, I designed some notches on the back side of the arched piece to resist warping. I managed to print five in a row with little visible warping.
The tower roofline was intended only to be the top of the roof; rather than wait for the whole wall to print, I instead glued this piece onto a 1/16" (1.5mm) sheet styrene. This piece has an inset tab on its bottom edge so there's a better gluing surface.
The storefront needs a vertical fill pattern to look realistic. Diagonally-banded stripes just don't appear very often on real buildings. I adjusted Skeinforge's fill angle attribute to either 0 or 90 degrees until the final external surface had a vertical pattern. I also had to adjust the extrusion width over thickness ratio to get a more solid final surface. I also added extra "trim" pieces at the top and bottom to hide the curves of the extrusion changing directions.

description.text:
Laser cut covered wagon cut from 1/8th inch thick craft plywood - could easily also be cut from 1/8th MDF or whatever you want.

My daughter (4th grade) is doing an 'Oregon Trail' section right now at school and was given the task of making a covered wagon. I created the design and cut it out and let her glue it together.

The front axel can rotate independently from the rest of the wagon for turning.

How to assemble

I found it best to lay one of the sides down flat and then glue the bench Foot Base, Seat, and Back into the notches, then the Rear Wagon Wall, and the Bottom. THEN you can attach the other side on top of all of those.

I used wood glue on everything (My daughter did most of the gluing. I just made a puddle of wood glue on a piece of scrap plastic bag and she used a tooth pick to dip into the glue and apply to the notches).

Once the main body of the wagon is stable enough, you can glue the Rear Axel support into the bottom of the wagon, and the Front Axel support into the front.

The front axel is the only real tricky part. The image above has all the major bits marked with arrows, and the image below has the parts laid out to show how they should go together. There's some photos of our finished wagon above that also show the axel that you might want to reference to get an idea of how its supposed to be assembled.

The two pieces that are rectangular and then have circular ends are for holding the bar at the front of the wagon that you use to steer. Glue them onto the front axel while also sliding the guide part in and then gluing caps on the end of the guide bar so it can work its way out.

Anyway, if you have trouble working it out, just ask, but its not a terribly complicated setup.
